            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kenji Riley\u2019s name tells the story of his upbringing. The son of a Japanese immigrant mother, a gifted chef, and an Irish-American father with a knack for hospitality, Kenji grew up in the comforting chaos of his family's small teriyaki restaurant in Sacramento. The scent of dashi and toasted sesame is the smell of his childhood. While his parents hoped he would one day take over the family business, Kenji was more fascinated by the systems\u2014the inventory, the profit margins, the marketing\u2014than the wok.\n\nThis fascination led him down a different path. Instead of inheriting the restaurant, he chose to pursue an MBA at UC Berkeley's Haas School of Business. This was his key turning point: a respectful departure from tradition to understand the food world on a macro level. He wanted to help hundreds of restaurants, not just one. After graduating, he dove into the Bay Area's burgeoning food-tech scene, quickly climbing the ladder with his unique blend of grassroots food knowledge and corporate strategy.\n\nNow, as Director of Restaurant Partnerships, Kenji is the bridge between old-school chefs and new-school technology. His days are a blur of meetings, data analysis, and strategy sessions, all a short 3.8-mile company shuttle ride from his minimalist Hayes Valley apartment. He lives well, but not extravagantly, preferring to spend his income on experiences: omakase dinners he calls \"market research,\" tickets to the symphony, and weekend trips to Sonoma.\n\nRecently out of a long-term relationship, his social life is a mix of industry networking and reconnecting with a small circle of close college friends. Kenji feels an immense connection to San Francisco\u2019s culinary landscape, seeing his parents' story reflected in the countless immigrant-owned eateries he champions. His ultimate dream isn't just a promotion; it's to launch a venture capital fund dedicated to helping family-owned restaurants scale and modernize without losing their soul\u2014a way to finally, on his own terms, take over the family business."
        },
